  "body": "## Description\r\n\r\nPresently Lighthouse will reconstruct the state _at_ the epoch requested for API calls like `/eth/v1/beacon/states/head/committees?epoch=2988`.\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/sigp/lighthouse/blob/564d7da656803f5e06e53a303972580be54500bf/beacon_node/http_api/src/lib.rs#L684-L686\r\n\r\nAs discovered experimentally by @jclapis and expanded on by @ajsutton, this isn't actually necessary, and we could be using a more recent state to calculate historic committees. Specifically I think we should use:\r\n\r\n* The `head` state if it's in range, or\r\n* The first state on a restore point after the requested epoch (otherwise).\r\n\r\nThis will work because the only dependencies for the committee computation at epoch `n` are:\r\n\r\n- The active validator indices (which are known at any epoch >= `n - 1`).\r\n- The randao mix from epoch `n - 2` (`n - MIN_SEED_LOOKAHEAD - 1`).\r\n\r\nSpec: https://github.com/ethereum/consensus-specs/blob/dev/specs/phase0/beacon-chain.md#get_beacon_committee\r\n\r\nWe can determine whether a request epoch `n` is in range of the head state using this check:\r\n\r\n```\r\nn >= head_epoch - EPOCHS_PER_HISTORICAL_VECTOR + MIN_SEED_LOOKAHEAD + 2\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhich arises from solving `n - 2 >= head_epoch - EPOCHS_PER_HISTORICAL_VECTOR + 1` (i.e. randao epoch needs to be the last entry of the randao array, or newer).\r\n\r\nSimilarly because the maximum SPRP of 8192 is only 256 epochs, then the state at slot `(epoch.start_slot() // SPRP + 1) * SPRP` will always be in range for `epoch`.\r\n\r\n## Version\r\n\r\nLighthouse v2.3.1\r\n\r\n## Additional Info\r\n\r\nDiscord thread where this was discovered: https://discord.com/channels/605577013327167508/618981555985186827/986483837943038022\r\n",
